    "title": "Zero oracle prices are accepted as valid debt/collateral valuations",
    "locations": [
      "0x05bfa9157e92690b179033ca2f6dd1e86b25ea4d/contracts/misc/AaveOracle.sol:93",
      "0x05bfa9157e92690b179033ca2f6dd1e86b25ea4d/contracts/misc/AaveOracle.sol:96",
      "0x05bfa9157e92690b179033ca2f6dd1e86b25ea4d/contracts/protocol/lendingpool/LendingPool.sol:861",
      "0x05bfa9157e92690b179033ca2f6dd1e86b25ea4d/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/GenericLogic.sol:186",
      "0x2409af0251dcb89ee3dee572629291f9b087c668/contracts/misc/AaveOracle.sol:93",
      "0x2409af0251dcb89ee3dee572629291f9b087c668/contracts/protocol/lendingpool/LendingPool.sol:861"
    ],
    "claim": "The oracle forwards missing/invalid sources to the fallback oracle and returns whatever value comes back, including 0, while borrow/accounting code treats that 0 as a legitimate asset price. A zero-priced reserve therefore contributes 0 to amountInETH and totalDebtInETH instead of reverting.",
    "impact": "If any listed asset ever resolves to price 0, users can borrow that reserve essentially for free, or keep existing debt from being counted in health-factor checks. That can drain all liquidity from the affected reserve and leave the protocol with unliquidatable bad debt.",
    "paths": [
      "Source is unset or primary feed falls back to a fallback oracle that returns 0",
      "Attacker deposits any normal collateral and borrows the zero-priced reserve",
      "LendingPool._executeBorrow computes amountInETH == 0, so validation ignores the new debt and the borrow succeeds"
    ]
  },
  {
